{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1adfe6d3-91c9-4677-8727-6c08fa49a64e","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates one instance **per HTTP request** — each request is a natural scope boundary. In MAUI, **there are no HTTP requests**, so there's no automatic scope. `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`, giving you a single `DbContext` for the entire app lifetime. That's why data \"leaks\" across navigations.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — gives a fresh `DbContext` per injection:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Create scopes manually** with `IServiceScopeFactory` if you need scoped behavior tied to a page/operation:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n3. **Use a DbContext factory** (EF Core's built-in pattern):\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   // Then inject IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext> and call CreateDbContext()\n   ```\n\nOption 3 (`AddDbContextFactory`) is generally the recommended approach for non-HTTP apps.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"84dfd7fe-740e-4dcc-8e70-e3a50da993e1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common gotcha when moving from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping, specifically with `AddScoped` and `DbContext`. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request scope — so `AddScoped` behaves essentially like `AddSingleton`, meaning the same DbContext instance lives for the entire app lifetime.","outputTokens":446,"requestId":"D454:86E8:1D41266:20EB640:6A07C482"},"id":"c07485e7-4d45-4eba-88ca-b0e05c4c11ee","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:12:44.128Z","parentId":"a2b4595b-0928-4cb9-991f-b6d72ed68bc2"}
